  <Docs>
    <summary>
            This rule ensure that every flags, enumarations decorated with the <c>[System.Flags]</c>
            attribute, does not contain a <c>0</c> value. This value would not be usable in boolean
            operations.
            </summary>
    <remarks>To be added.</remarks>
    <example>
            Bad example (using 0 for a normal value):
            <code>
            [Flags]
            enum Access {
            	Read = 0,
            	Write = 1
            }
            </code></example>
    <example>
            Bad example (using None):
            <code>
            [Flags]
            enum Access {
            	// this is less severe since the name of the 0 value helps
            	None = 0,
            	Read = 1,
            	Write = 2
            }
            </code></example>
    <example>
            Good example:
            <code>
            [Flags]
            enum Access {
            	Read = 1,
            	Write = 2
            }
            </code></example>
    <example>
            Bad example (using 0 for a normal value):
            <code>
            [Flags]
            enum Access {
            	Read = 0,
            	Write = 1
            }
            </code></example>
    <example>
            Bad example (using None):
            <code>
            [Flags]
            enum Access {
            	// this is less severe since the name of the 0 value helps
            	None = 0,
            	Read = 1,
            	Write = 2
            }
            </code></example>
    <example>
            Good example:
            <code>
            [Flags]
            enum Access {
            	Read = 1,
            	Write = 2
            }
            </code></example>
  </Docs>
